title: Unexpected behavior with _map and _pickBy
body:
It seems like using `_.map([...], _pickBy)` is resulting in very unexpected behavior.  All examples are run in the REPL on https://lodash.com/docs/4.17.5#pickBy

`_.map([{'a': null}, {'a': 'x'}, {'a' : 'y'},{'a': null}, {'a': 'z'}], _.pickBy)` => `[{}, {}, {}, {}, {}]`
`_.map([{'a': 'x'}, {'a' : 'y'},{'a': null}, {'a': 'z'}], _.pickBy)` => `[{'a': 'x'}, {}, {}, {}]`
`_.map([{'a': 'x'}, {'a' : 'y'},{'a': null}, {'a': 'zzzz'}], _.pickBy)` => `[{'a': 'x'}, {}, {}, {'a' : 'zzzz'}]` (the field is not present in the last object with 2 or 3 `z` characters either, but appears once you add 4)

interestingly, the behavior is as expected when creating a lambda around _.pickBy:
`_.map([{'a': null}, {'a': 'x'}, {'a' : 'y'},{'a': null}, {'a': 'z'}], (v) => _.pickBy(v))` => `[{}, {'a': 'x'}, {'a': 'y'}, {}, {'a': 'z'}]`
`_.map([{'a': 'x'}, {'a' : 'y'},{'a': null}, {'a': 'z'}], (v) => _.pickBy(v))` => `[{'a': 'x'}, {'a': 'y'}, {}, {'a': 'z'}]`
`_.map([{'a': 'x'}, {'a' : 'y'},{'a': null}, {'a': 'zzzz'}], (v) => _.pickBy(v))` => `[{'a': 'x'}, {'a': 'y'}, {}, {'a' : 'zzzz'}]`

I haven't been able to detect any pattern to why sometimes fields are picked or not in the first pattern, these are just some use-cases i came across trying to determine the behavior

title: _.isFinite/isInteger/isLength returns false from Number() constructor
body:
```
_.isFinite(new Number(0)) => false
_.isInteger(new Number(0)) => false
a = {length: new Number(1)}
_.isLength(a.length) => false
```

As such, the _.isFinite implementation is different from the global isFinite implementation. Consider this case:

```
_.isFinite([]) => false
isFinite([]) => true
```

I believe this is a bug. The code only checks that the value passed in is of `type x == 'number'` but it doesn't check them as `instanceof Number`. The only correct check I saw is from the _.isNumber() method which checks for isObjectLike(). Maybe have them all use _.isNumber to first check?

title: Use "memoizeCapped" instead of "memoize" while caching the results
body:
Use of `memoize` function and caching result for every `path` provided for `get` function can lead to memory leaks when `path` variable will be changed frequently for the following calls.

The issue is linked only with `lodash.get` installable package:
https://github.com/lodash/lodash/tree/4.4.2-npm-packages/lodash.get

The same `get` function from the main `lodash` repository uses `memoizeCapped` which limits the cached values to 500.

title: `initCloneArray()` to use `new`
body:
### Issue

Currently, in the NPM version, cloning an instance of an `Array` subclass raises a `TypeError` because ES6 classes require the `new` when instantiating.

Unlike the `Array` constructor, subclasses don't allow function constructors.

### Example

```javascript
import * as Lodash from 'lodash';

class MyArray extends Array {}

const instance = new MyArray();

Lodash.clone(instance); // TypeError: Class constructor MyArray cannot be invoked without 'new'
```

### Resolution

Make [`initCloneArray()`](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/npm/_initCloneArray.js#L16) instantiate the new array using the `new` keyword.

Note that `master` [already fixes this](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/master/.internal/baseClone.js#L131) but the npm branch doesn't seem up to date. So maybe the fix is simply to update that branch / the underlying modules.

title: Feature request: `defaultTo` with multiple values
body:
Hi,
I really like to use `_.defaultTo(a, b)` because it is much more readable than `a || b` (and works with `0`, `false` and `''` as valid values for `a`).
Sometimes I find myself doing this:
```js
var foo = _.defaultTo(bar, baz);
foo = _.defaultTo(foo, bax);
```
or its less readable sibling:
```js
var foo = _.defaultTo(_.defaultTo(bar, baz), bax);
```

I wish I could do this:
```js
var foo = _.defaultTo(bar, baz, bax);
```
Which returns the first argument whose value is not one of `undefined`, `null` or `NaN`.
Maybe its name should be different, like `_.defaultToAny`.

Any chance you're ever going to support such functionality?
Thank you very much!

title: `_.flow` does not preserve initial function arity
body:
Using flow does not preserve the arity of the first function passed in, so `_.curry` won't work and you need to use `_.curryN`.

```js
let add = (x, y) => x + y
let double = x => x * 2

// Returns 10
 _.flow(add, double)(1, 4)

// Throws Exception
_.curry(_.flow(add, double))(1)(4)

// Returns 10
_.curryN(2, _.flow(add, double))(1)(4)
```

More specifically this is 0:

```js
_.flow(add, double).length
```



I've worked around this by defining a combo flow/curry function (forgive the silly name 😄 ):

```js
let flurry = (...fns) => _.curryN(fns[0].length, _.flow(...fns))
```

This seems like a bug in `_.flow`.

In clamp.js as of d985dbff

```
function clamp(number, lower, upper) {
  number = +number
  lower = +lower
  upper = +upper
  lower = lower === lower ? lower : 0
  upper = upper === upper ? upper : 0
  if (number === number) {
    number = number <= upper ? number : upper
    number = number >= lower ? number : lower
  }
  return number
}
```

Is there a reason why `number === number` is checked? Wouldn't it always evaluate to true?

This is not a contrived issue, the problem arose while calculating taxes with Lodash and feeding the results to government forms that reported errors in calculations.

I'm using v4.17.4 via [LodashGS](https://github.com/oshliaer/lodashgs).

Here's my workaround that feels like an ugly hack:

    _.round(_.round(value, 3), 2);

title: rAF support for debounce/throtte (#3560)
body:
### Adds an additional option to debounce and throttle
if the option `useRAF` is `true` and `requestAnimationFrame()` is available on the `root` object (e.g. `window` in a browser environment), it will be used for timing instead of `setTimeout()`.

This allows for very smooth and performant throttling of rapid firing events like scroll, resize, etc.

Feedback, comments, etc are much appreciated :)

title: _.words handles numbers differently when converting cases
body:
Several previous issues state that numbers are considered words, but regular language strings do this differently from camelCase or snakeCase.

When:

1. `_.words('my 1st birthday')`
2. `_.words('my_1st_birthday')`
3. `_.words('my1stBirthday')`

Expected:
All would return either 
`["my", "1", "st", "birthday"] `
or 
`["my", "1st", "birthday"]`
 
Actual:

1. `["my", "1st", "birthday"]`
2. `["my", "1", "st", "birthday"]`
3. `["my", "1", "st", "birthday"]`

Is it expected that 'nth' is viewed differently in a regular string vs camel or snake case?

title: Feature Request: _.throttle using requestAnimationFrame via options flag
body:
Hi there!

Similar to #1165 (hat tip to @MeoMix), but instead of a whole new specialized function, what if we just add support to `_.throttle` directly, behind an options flag (eg. `options.requestAnimationFrame=true` perhaps?).

`_.throttle` could then degrade gracefully to its default implementation (with a default 1000/60 wait interval) whenever `window.requestAnimationFrame` is unavailable (such as in NodeJS).

Anyone else in favor of this? I, for one, would love to have this sort of utility within Lodash itself! 😀
